To solve the given system of linear equations using matrix methods, we first write the system in the matrix form AX = B, where A is the matrix of coefficients, X is the column matrix of variables, and B is the column matrix of constants.

$$
\begin{bmatrix}
3 & 5 \\
2 & -4
\end{bmatrix}
\begin{bmatrix}
x \\
y
\end{bmatrix}
=
\begin{bmatrix}
13 \\
2
\end{bmatrix}
$$

Now, we will find the inverse of matrix A and multiply both sides of the equation by the inverse to find the solution.

Matrix A:
$$
\begin{bmatrix}
3 & 5 \\
2 & -4
\end{bmatrix}
$$

To find the inverse of a 2x2 matrix, we use the formula:

$$
A^{-1} = \frac{1}{\text{det}(A)}
\begin{bmatrix}
d & -b \\
-c & a
\end{bmatrix}
$$

where a, b, c, and d are the elements of the matrix A, and det(A) is the determinant of A.

In our case, a = 3, b = 5, c = 2, and d = -4. The determinant of A is:

$$
\text{det}(A) = ad - bc = (3)(-4) - (5)(2) = -12 - 10 = -22
$$

Now, we can find the inverse of A:

$$
A^{-1} = \frac{1}{-22}
\begin{bmatrix}
-4 & -5 \\
-2 & 3
\end{bmatrix}
=
\begin{bmatrix}
\frac{2}{11} & \frac{5}{22} \\
\frac{1}{11} & -\frac{3}{22}
\end{bmatrix}
$$

Now, we can multiply both sides of the equation by the inverse of A:

$$
A^{-1}AX = A^{-1}B
$$

Since $A^{-1}A = I$ (the identity matrix), we have:

$$
X = A^{-1}B
$$

Now, we multiply the inverse of A by B:

$$
\begin{bmatrix}
\frac{2}{11} & \frac{5}{22} \\
\frac{1}{11} & -\frac{3}{22}
\end{bmatrix}
\begin{bmatrix}
13 \\
2
\end{bmatrix}
=
\begin{bmatrix}
\frac{2}{11}(13) + \frac{5}{22}(2) \\
\frac{1}{11}(13) - \frac{3}{22}(2)
\end{bmatrix}
=
\begin{bmatrix}
\frac{26}{11} + \frac{10}{22} \\
\frac{13}{11} - \frac{6}{22}
\end{bmatrix}
=
\begin{bmatrix}
\frac{31}{11} \\
\frac{10}{11}
\end{bmatrix}
$$

So, the solution to the system of linear equations is:

$$
x = \frac{31}{11}, \quad y = \frac{10}{11}
$$
